---- MODULE VoucherTransfer ----
1. A set of 3 vouchers (V) and their corresponding state predicates for each voucher, which define whether it has been transferred or not; this includes its source VTP status as well as destination DHs' prepared states. We also have a specification that all SHs must receive the "Transfer" message from one of these 3 predefined sources (src1/2) and then send out their own initial state, which is just an empty set to indicate they are waiting for it;
2. A spec about DH's status as well as VTP's type correctness invariant: All SH must have sent Prepared messages before the Transfer action can be performed (vsh1 and vsh3 in this case), while all DH should receive these "Prepare" from their corresponding source. The only way to change a state is by adding an element; hence, we use SetAddAll(E). We also define SH/DHSend messages based on the above two sets of states and update our current (SH) / final (FINAL DHsSend), which are then used as part of VTPConsistent' invariant.
3. A spec about all 9 possible actions that can be performed in this transaction, including: Source SH sends a Prepared message to the Destination; both source and destination send out their initial state (which is just an empty set); if either party decides not participating anymore they will simply abort immediately by sending "Abort". The action names are self-explanatory.
4. Invariance of these two sets: VTPTypeOK / Consistent in this case checks that the source and destination DHs must be equal, i.e., all elements from src1/2 can only participate with each other (but not any others). If they do decide to abort at some point during the transaction process then it is considered a "deadlock" state whereby neither side will proceed anymore;
5 The final spec for VTPTypeOK / Consistent. This theorem asserts that, based on our above actions and invariance definitions (which we called invariant), this specification of 9 possible states/actions can indeed capture the behavior described by two-phase commit protocol mentioned earlier - each side is only considered "prepared" to transfer a voucher if they have received Prepare message from their counterparts, but then both parties must decide together (in our case these are source and destination SHs) before committing or aborting the transaction.
====